---
title: "Working with Slack"
---

```{r, include = FALSE}
knitr::opts_chunk$set(
  collapse = TRUE,
  comment = "#>"
)
```

```{r setup}
library(promoutils)
library(dplyr)
```


Using the Slack API to schedule messages.
First make sure you are authorized to work with the Slack API:

```{r}
keys_check()
```

If not, see the [Setting Up Slack](article/slack_app) article.

Once you have set up your Slack access, you can use the Slack API to access
the rOpenSci Slack space using httr2 directly or via the promoutils helper functions.


### Posting messages immediately

By default all messages are posted in the `#testing-api` channel which is great 
for playing and testing, but when you're ready to post for real you can change 
this with the `channel` argument.

```{r}
slack_posts_write("Testing immediately posting in the Vignette!")
```

We can get a list of messages in this channel:
```{r}
slack_messages("testing-api")
```

And we can clean this up with:

```{r}
m <- slack_messages("testing-api") |>
  slack_message_rm()
```

Check that it's gone
```{r}
slack_messages("testing-api")
```

```{r include=FALSE}
# Silently clean up from the vignette
slack_scheduled_list() |>
  filter(
    channel == "testing-api",
    #text == "Testing schedules in the Vignette!"
  ) |>
  slack_scheduled_rm()
```


### Scheduling messages

Let's schedule a message for tomorrow. 

```{r}
slack_posts_write(
  "Testing scheduled messages in the Vignette!",
  when = Sys.Date() + lubridate::days(1)
)
```

- If `when = "now"`, `slack_posts_write()` will post immediately (default)
- If scheduled, `slack_posts_write()` will also post a copy of the message and 
it's date to scheduled in the private channel, `#admin-scheduled`, 
for quick checking of currently scheduled messages when you're in the Slack app.

![](slack_eg.png){fig-alt = ""}

See the currently scheduled messages according to the Slack API
```{r}
slack_scheduled_list()
```


To delete currently scheduled messages you need to know the `channel_id` and the message `id`. 
We can get these from `slack_list_scheduled()` or we can supply the data frame directly as we did above.

```{r}
m <- slack_scheduled_list()
slack_scheduled_rm(m)
```

Note that `slack_scheduled_rm()` also removes the message posted to the `#admin-scheduled`
channel, so that channel *should* be a faithful representation of messages currently 
scheduled via the API.

```{r}
slack_scheduled_list()
```

However, after posts have been sent, you'll need to clean up `#admin-scheduled`
with a call to `slack_cleanup()` which will remove any message in `#admin-scheduled` that isn't also in Slack's internal scheduled messages list.

```{r}
slack_cleanup()
```